<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920107-0044</DOCNO><DOCID>920107-0044.</DOCID><HL>   Oil Firms Plan 1.3% Rise   In Outlays, Survey Finds</HL><DATE>01/07/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4</SO><IN>PETROLEUM (PET)</IN><NS>PETROLEUM MARKET (PET)</NS><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   NEW YORK -- Salomon Brothers Inc. said oil companies planto raise 1992 spending on exploration and production a slight1.3% to $53.7 billion, confirming the industry's nervousoutlook.   A survey by the securities firm found that only spendingplans outside of North America went up; 80 companies plan toboost expenditures 9.1%. Spending in the U.S. will continueto decline, the survey found. The survey was made up of 241companies.</LP><TEXT>   Companies are basing their budgets on an average oil priceof $20.40 a barrel and an average natural gas price of $1.62per thousand cubic feet. Those prices are slightly abovetoday's spot market quotes.   In addition, the survey says, companies will shift more oftheir budgets to development projects and away fromexploration. Furthermore, because of the prolonged weaknessin natural gas prices, energy concerns will shift more oftheir focus to oil projects.   The survey also found that for the first time a majorityof companies view buying reserves as a better option thandrilling for them. A record 72% are actively looking topurchase reserves, primarily oil, Salomon said.</TEXT></DOC>